<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36105h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36105h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36105h"> 105(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> counterskarp <font color="red"><sup><teeny>|a</teeny></sup></font>(place de la / Contrescarpe)<font color="red"><sup><teeny>a|</teeny></sup></font> <small>Black</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36105h"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Paris, described in a recent German account as the greatest fortress in the world, possesses three perfect distinct rings of defences. &hellip; The enceinte (&ldquo;the fortifications&rdquo; of the guide-books) is of plain bastion trace, without ravelins but with a deep dry ditch (escarp, but not <mark>counterscarp</mark> revetted). <small> &ldquo;PARIS&rdquo; <a name="EBPS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBPS"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 804b</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The addition is written in ink. Counterscarp: the outer walls or slope of the [fortifying] ditch which supports the covered way; sometimes, the whole covered way with the glacis. </mm> </dd></dl>
